    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Slender, robust, cylindrical fish with a pointed snout and large eye and mouth. Dorsal fin separated into spine and ray portions and depressible into a groove. Row of small triangular finlets behind both dorsal and anal fins and stiff, forked tail with a pair of fleshy lateral keels at its base. Dorsal half of body greenish with numerous oblique wavy zig-zag dark bands, ventral half silvery-white.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_4036",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 50 cm length and a mass of 2 kg, but typically about 30 cm (larger reported specimens now recognized as different species).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_4037",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread in Pacific, but absent from Indian Ocean except for South Africa. Previous reports from the Atlantic are now recognised as <i>S. colias</i> and those from northern Indian Ocean as <i>S. australasicus.</i></p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Western Cape to KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_4038",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Form pelagic schools in coastal waters, usually segregated by size but may be mixed with other species, such as Maasbanker (Atlantic horse mackerel) or Pilchard. Migrate southwards during summer and back northwards during winter. Targeted by both purse seine and beach seine fisheries and by recreational and commercial line fishers. Reach sexual maturity at a length of about 40 cm and an age of 3 years.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_4039",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Predatory, feeding mainly on zooplankton, squid or small fish, depending on their size.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_4040",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Spawn along the Western and Eastern Cape coasts in June to September and off KZN July-December. Eggs are laid in batches, with total number of eggs per female ranging from 100,000–400,000. Eggs and larvae are pelagic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_4041",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Colour pattern distinctive.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_4042",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
